04166nam a22005055i 9780226519654DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20101987ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226519654  a(DE-B1597)535697  a(OCoLC)1135611208  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPN47b.M45 1987 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809.93355a809/.933551 aMeltzer, Françoise, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSalome and the Dance of Writing :bPortraits of Mimesis in Literature /cFrançoise Meltzer. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2010] 4c©1987  a1 online resource (233 p.) :bfrontispiece  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Salome and the Dance of Writing -- t2. The Spearpoint of Troilus -- t3. The Golden Calf and the Golden Ass -- t4. Still Life -- t5. Sleight of Hand -- tEchoes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow does literature imagine its own powers of representation? Françoise Meltzer attempts to answer this question by looking at how the portrait—the painted portrait, framed—appears in various literary texts. Alien to the verbal system of the text yet mimetic of the gesture of writing, the textual portrait becomes a telling measure of literature's views on itself, on the politics of representation, and on the power of writing. Meltzer's readings of textual portraits—in the Gospel writers and Huysmans, Virgil and Stendhal, the Old Testament and Apuleius, Hawthorne and Poe, Kafka and Rousseau, Walter Scott and Mme de Lafayette—reveal an interplay of control and subversion: writing attempts to veil the visual and to erase the sensual in favor of "meaning," while portraiture, with its claims to bringing the natural object to "life," resists and eludes such control. Meltzer shows how this tension is indicative of a politics of repression and subversion intrinsic to the very act of representation. Throughout, she raises and illuminates fascinating issues: about the relation of flattery to caricature, the nature of the uncanny, the relation of representation to memory and history, the narcissistic character of representation, and the interdependency of representation and power. Writing, thinking, speaking, dreaming, acting—the extent to which these are all controlled by representation must, Meltzer concludes, become "consciously unconscious." In the textual portrait, she locates the moment when this essential process is both revealed and repressed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMimesis in literature. 0aPortraits in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  awriter, literature, literary, mimesis, english major, college, university, higher education, representation, portrait, textual, politics, political, gospel, huysman, virgil, stendhal, old testament, apuleius, hawthorne, poe, kafka, rousseau, walter scott, control, subversive, portraiture, analysis, critical, critique, troilus, golden calf, manifesto.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989z978311066784440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226519654423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226519654/original  a978-3-11-066784-4  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989c1960d1989  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles